pr_body: Add module path to resolved resource name
pr_review_comments: [{'comment_id': 463475068, 'comment_body': '1. Please check: do we still have classes starting with "sun/" in Java 11? I thought everything was migrated to module jdk.internal, but I might be wrong. Also, in that case, the package name would start with "com/sun". So the second and third condition may not be fixing anything.\r\n2. Even with java classes, we can only guess which module they belong to. So it may be better to fix the unit test than to provide a workaround that does not really reflect the behavior of the JDK (which can find classes by their package name, but does not prepend "java.base"). Do you know why?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 31, 8, 25, 36, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'cyrille-artho', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 463612487, 'comment_body': "Let's use ClassLoader.getModule to determine what prefix should be used, and use that as an extra parameter to getResource. This is how it seems to work in JDK 11, and avoids introducing a different behavior in JPF.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 31, 13, 31, 58, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'cyrille-artho', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 463613913, 'comment_body': 'If the module is unnamed (getModule().isNamed() returns false), then we just load the resource as below, without a module. Otherwise, we use the module of the given class loader as the module name (the additional parameter).', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 7, 31, 13, 34, 36, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'cyrille-artho', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 464514230, 'comment_body': 'Module.isName is missing in model class of Module class. Hence, as a first step should I add and implement the missing method in the model class.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 3, 16, 11, 41, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'yuvaraj-anbarasan', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 464565791, 'comment_body': 'Yes, please do that. Perhaps you can get the right module name from the host JVM.', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2020, 8, 3, 17, 42, 40, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'cyrille-artho', 'type': 'User'}]
